Balancing Dataset¶

We need to balance the dataset so that about the same number of instances are within each class. We will take the observations of this dataset and evenly distribute them into five bins. We first sort the data by the ChildPoverty values, and then create the bins containing the 25th, 50th, 75th, and 100th percentiles of the sorted data. We should balance the dataset for both the training and testing set. This ensures that the model is trained on an unbiased dataset and provides an accurate representation of the data so that the majority of the data is not focused on one class.

In [ ]:

The graph above shows the unbalanced distribution of classes before any processing. This dataset is extremely unbalanced, with the 1st class completely overwhelming the other classes. This would skew the accuracy results of our models as it would best predict test data belonging to the first class and perform poorly with any other test data belonging to any other class.

Pre-Processing and Initial Modeling¶

We will be building 3 different perceptron models. Each perceptron model with have:

  • Vectorized Gradient Calculation
  • Mini-batching
  • Loss Cross Entropy
  • Proper Glorot Initialization

The three different perceptron models are:

  1. Normal Perceptron Model

  2. Normalized-Continuous Data Model: This model will be trained using the dataset whose continuous features have been normalized.

  3. Normalized-Continuous Data Model & One-Hot Encoding Model: This model will be trained using the dataset whose continuous features have been normalized and one-hot encoded.

For comparing the performance of all three models, we will use the following parameters. We will compare the performance of all three models towards the end of this section.

Normal Perceptron Model¶

Base Model¶

In [ ]:
#Example adapted from https://github.com/rasbt/python-machine-learning-book/blob/master/code/ch12/ch12.ipynb
#Original Author: Sebastian Raschka

from scipy.special import expit
import sys

class TwoLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden    # first hidden layer nodes

        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        # One-Hot encode labels
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights with small random numbers
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_)
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))

        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_output_
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2,
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2):
        # compute L2-regularization cost using W1, W2, W3

        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1 ** 2) + np.mean(W2 ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2):
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A3)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2)
        
        return cost + L2_term
In [ ]:
# adding feedforward and fit and predict functions
class TwoLayerPerceptron(TwoLayerPerceptronBase):
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, b1, b2):
        """
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a3 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z2 : layer inputs 
        """

        # feedforward into first hidden layer
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)

        # feedforward into second hidden layer
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)

        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        pass
    
    
    def predict(self, X):
        _, _, _, _, A3 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2)

        y_pred = np.argmax(A3, axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        # learn weights from training data
        
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2, = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            # feedforward all instances
            A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3 = self._feedforward(X_data,self.W1,self.W2,self.b1,self.b2)
            
            cost = self._cost(A3,Y_enc,self.W1,self.W2)
            self.cost_.append(cost)

            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Y_enc=Y_enc,
            W1=self.W1, W2=self.W2)

            self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1
            self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2

            self.b1 -= self.eta * gradb1
            self.b2 -= self.eta * gradb2
            
        return self

Vectorized Gradient Computation¶

The gradient calculations can be optimized using vectors instead of for-loops. We only need to modify the _get_gradient function.

In [ ]:
class TwoLayerPerceptronVectorized(TwoLayerPerceptron):
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V2 = -2*(Y_enc-A3)*A3*(1-A3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)

        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2

Mini-batching¶

Instead of considering the entire dataset, this model trains itself using sub-datasets, increasing the model's speed.

In [ ]:
# adding mini-batching to Two Layer Perceptron class
class TLPMiniBatch(TwoLayerPerceptronVectorized):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches

        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        # learn weights from training data with mini-batch
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []

        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            eta = self.eta

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A3,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, 
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2)

                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2

                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum

                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2
                

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

Cross Entropy Loss¶

Using Cross Entropy Loss allows us to quantify how our model is performing. We want our Cross Entropy Loss to be as close to 0 as possible.

In [ ]:
# add cross entropy to TLPMiniBatch class
class TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatch):
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2):
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A3)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A3))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2)

        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        # compute gradient step using backpropagation

        # vectorized backpropagation
        V2 = (A3-Y_enc)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2

Glorot Initialization¶

Glorot Initialization allows our model to initialize the weights using a uniform distribution.

In [ ]:
# derive class with Glorot Initialization
class TLPBetterInitial(TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):             
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights Glorot and He normalization
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 
        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2

Third Layer Perceptron¶

We've developed our two layer perceptron with the different optimization techniques, but now we will be adding a third hidden layer.

In [ ]:
from scipy.special import expit
import sys

class ThreeLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, n_hidden2 = 15, C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden    # first hidden layer nodes
        self.n_hidden2 = n_hidden2  # second hidden layer nodes

        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        # One-Hot encode labels
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights with small random numbers
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_)
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_hidden2
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))

        W3_num_elems = (self.n_hidden2)*self.n_output_
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W3_num_elems)
        W3 = W3.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden2)
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, b1, b2, b3
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2, W3):
        # compute L2-regularization cost using W1, W2, W3

        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1 ** 2) + np.mean(W2 ** 2) + np.mean(W3 ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A4,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3):
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A4)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3)
        
        return cost + L2_term

# adding feedforward and fit and predict functions
class ThreeLayerPerceptron(ThreeLayerPerceptronBase):
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, b1, b2, b3):
        """
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer1.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer1 -> hidden layer 2.
        W3: Weight matrix for hidden layer2 -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a4 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z3 : layer inputs 
        """

        # feedforward into first hidden layer
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)

        # feedforward into second hidden layer
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)

        # feedforward into third hidden layer/output layer
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._sigmoid(Z3)

        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, Z1, Z2, Z3, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3):
        pass
    
    
    def predict(self, X):
        _, _, _, _, _, _, A4 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3)

        y_pred = np.argmax(A4, axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        # learn weights from training data
        
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3 = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            # feedforward all instances
            A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4 = self._feedforward(X_data,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.b1,self.b2,self.b3)
            
            cost = self._cost(A4,Y_enc,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3)
            self.cost_.append(cost)

            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Y_enc=Y_enc,
            W1=self.W1, W2=self.W2, W3=self.W3)

            self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1
            self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2
            self.W3 -= self.eta * gradW3

            self.b1 -= self.eta * gradb1
            self.b2 -= self.eta * gradb2
            self.b3 -= self.eta * gradb3
            
        return self

Optimization Techniques¶

In [ ]:
class ThreeLayerPerceptronVectorized(ThreeLayerPerceptron):
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, Z1, Z2, Z3, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3):
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V3 = -2*(Y_enc-A4)*A4*(1-A4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)

        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3

# adding mini-batching to Two Layer Perceptron class
class T3LPMiniBatch(ThreeLayerPerceptronVectorized):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches

        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        # learn weights from training data with mini-batch
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape) # for momentum

        # create arrays for average magnitude of weights
        self.grad_w1_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w2_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w3_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []

        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            eta = self.eta

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []

            self.grad_w1_batch = []
            self.grad_w2_batch = []
            self.grad_w3_batch = []

            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A4,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2,self.W3)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3,
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3)

                # append average magnitude of weights to array
                self.grad_w1_batch.append(np.mean(np.abs(gradW1)))
                self.grad_w2_batch.append(np.mean(np.abs(gradW2)))
                self.grad_w3_batch.append(np.mean(np.abs(gradW3)))

                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2, eta * gradW3

                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev)) # update with momentum

                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3
            
            # turn lists into arrays
            self.grad_w1_batch = np.array(self.grad_w1_batch)
            self.grad_w2_batch = np.array(self.grad_w2_batch)
            self.grad_w3_batch = np.array(self.grad_w3_batch)

            # average the average magnitude of weights
            self.grad_w1_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w1_batch)
            self.grad_w2_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w2_batch)
            self.grad_w3_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w3_batch)

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# add cross entropy to TLPMiniBatch class
class T3LPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(T3LPMiniBatch):
    def _cost(self,A4,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3):
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A4)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A4))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3)

        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, Z1, Z2, Z3, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3):
        # compute gradient step using backpropagation

        # vectorized backpropagation
        V3 = (A4-Y_enc) # <- this is only line that changed
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3

from scipy.special import expit
import sys

class FourLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, n_hidden2 = 15, n_hidden3 = 7, C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden    # first hidden layer nodes
        self.n_hidden2 = n_hidden2  # second hidden layer nodes
        self.n_hidden3 = n_hidden3  # third hidden layer nodes

        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        # One-Hot encode labels
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights with small random numbers
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_)
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_hidden2
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))

        W3_num_elems = (self.n_hidden2)*self.n_hidden3
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W3_num_elems)
        W3 = W3.reshape(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden2)
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))

        W4_num_elems = (self.n_hidden3)*self.n_output_
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W4_num_elems)
        W4 = W4.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden3)
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, b1, b2, b3, b4
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        # compute L2-regularization cost using W1, W2, W3, W4

        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1 ** 2) + np.mean(W2 ** 2) + np.mean(W3 ** 2) + np.mean(W4 ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A5,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3,W4):
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A5)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3, W4)
        
        return cost + L2_term

# adding feedforward and fit and predict functions
class FourLayerPerceptron(FourLayerPerceptronBase):
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, W4, b1, b2, b3, b4):
        """
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer1.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer1 -> hidden layer2.
        W3: Weight matrix for hidden layer2 -> hidden layer3.
        W4: Weight matrix for hidden layer3 -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a5 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z4 : layer inputs 
        """

        # feedforward into first hidden layer
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)

        # feedforward into second hidden layer
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)

        # feedforward into third hidden layer
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._sigmoid(Z3)

        # feedforward into fourth hidden layer
        Z4 = W4 @ A4 + b4
        A5 = self._sigmoid(Z4)

        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        pass
    
    
    def predict(self, X):
        _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, A5 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4)

        y_pred = np.argmax(A5, axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        # learn weights from training data
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4 = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            # feedforward all instances
            A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5 = self._feedforward(X_data,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.b1,self.b2,self.b3,self.b4)
            
            cost = self._cost(A5,Y_enc,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4)
            self.cost_.append(cost)

            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4,Y_enc=Y_enc,
            W1=self.W1, W2=self.W2, W3=self.W3, W4=self.W4)

            self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1
            self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2
            self.W3 -= self.eta * gradW3
            self.W4 -= self.eta * gradW4

            self.b1 -= self.eta * gradb1
            self.b2 -= self.eta * gradb2
            self.b3 -= self.eta * gradb3
            self.b4 -= self.eta * gradb4
            
        return self

class FourLayerPerceptronVectorized(FourLayerPerceptron):
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V4 = -2*(Y_enc-A5)*A5*(1-A5)
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)

        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4

# adding mini-batching to Two Layer Perceptron class
class FourLPMiniBatch(FourLayerPerceptronVectorized):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches

        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        # learn weights from training data with mini-batch
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W4_prev = np.zeros(self.W4.shape) # for momentum

        # create arrays for average magnitude of weights
        self.grad_w1_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w2_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w3_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w4_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []

        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()

            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            eta = self.eta

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []

            self.grad_w1_batch = []
            self.grad_w2_batch = []
            self.grad_w3_batch = []
            self.grad_w4_batch = []

            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.W4,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3,
                                                       self.b4,
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A5,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5,Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, 
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3,W4=self.W4)

                self.grad_w1_batch.append(np.mean(gradW1))
                self.grad_w2_batch.append(np.mean(gradW2))
                self.grad_w3_batch.append(np.mean(gradW3))
                self.grad_w4_batch.append(np.mean(gradW4))

                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2, eta * gradW3, eta * gradW4

                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W4 -= (rho_W4 + (self.alpha * rho_W4_prev)) # update with momentum

                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev, rho_W4_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4

            self.grad_w1_batch = np.array(self.grad_w1_batch)
            self.grad_w2_batch = np.array(self.grad_w2_batch)
            self.grad_w3_batch = np.array(self.grad_w3_batch)
            self.grad_w4_batch = np.array(self.grad_w4_batch)
            

            self.grad_w1_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w1_batch)
            self.grad_w2_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w2_batch)
            self.grad_w3_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w3_batch)
            self.grad_w4_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w4_batch)

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# add cross entropy to TLPMiniBatch class
class FourLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(FourLPMiniBatch):
    def _cost(self,A5,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3,W4):
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A5)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A5))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1,W2,W3,W4)

        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        # compute gradient step using backpropagation

        # vectorized backpropagation
        V4 = (A5-Y_enc) # <- this is only line that changed
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)

        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4

# derive class with Glorot Initialization
class FourLPBetterInitial(FourLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):             
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights Glorot and He normalization
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_))

        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden)) 

        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden3+ self.n_hidden2))
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden2))

        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden3))
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden3))
        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, b1, b2, b3, b4

The average gradient magnitude is highest from W4, followed by W3, W2, and W1. An interesting observation is that all magnitudes appear to converge towards 0, unlike the previous graph from the three layer perceptron model. Another detail is that the range for the average gradient magnitudes is much smaller (0.000 - 0.005) compared to that of the three layer perceptron graph (0.0 - 3.0).

From these details, we can assume that the model's performance increased from the 3 layer predecessor, although this may appear contradictory when we look at the four layer perceptron model's 24.99% accuracy in correctly predicting the child poverty rate.

from scipy.special import expit
import sys

class FiveLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, n_hidden2 = 15, n_hidden3 = 7, n_hidden4 = 3, C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden    # first hidden layer nodes
        self.n_hidden2 = n_hidden2  # second hidden layer nodes
        self.n_hidden3 = n_hidden3  # third hidden layer nodes
        self.n_hidden4 = n_hidden4  # fourth hidden layer nodes

        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        # One-Hot encode labels
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights with small random numbers
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_)
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_hidden2
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))

        W3_num_elems = (self.n_hidden2)*self.n_hidden3
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W3_num_elems)
        W3 = W3.reshape(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden2)
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))

        W4_num_elems = (self.n_hidden3)*self.n_hidden4
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W4_num_elems)
        W4 = W4.reshape(self.n_hidden4, self.n_hidden3)
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden4, 1))

        W5_num_elems = (self.n_hidden4)*self.n_output_
        W5 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W5_num_elems)
        W5 = W5.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden4)
        b5 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        # compute L2-regularization cost using W1, W2, W3, W4, W5

        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1 ** 2) + np.mean(W2 ** 2) + np.mean(W3 ** 2) + np.mean(W4 ** 2) + np.mean(W5 ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A6,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3,W4, W5):
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A6)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5)
        
        return cost + L2_term

# adding feedforward and fit and predict functions
class FiveLayerPerceptron(FiveLayerPerceptronBase):
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5):
        """
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer1.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer1 -> hidden layer2.
        W3: Weight matrix for hidden layer2 -> hidden layer3.
        W4: Weight matrix for hidden layer3 -> hidden layer4.
        W5: Weight matrix for hidden layer4 -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a6 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z5 : layer inputs 
        """

        # feedforward into first hidden layer
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)

        # feedforward into second hidden layer
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)

        # feedforward into third hidden layer
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._sigmoid(Z3)

        # feedforward into fourth hidden layer
        Z4 = W4 @ A4 + b4
        A5 = self._sigmoid(Z4)

        # feedforward into output layer
        Z5 = W5 @ A5 + b5
        A6 = self._sigmoid(Z5)

        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Z5, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        pass
    
    
    def predict(self, X):
        _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, A6 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5)

        y_pred = np.argmax(A6, axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        # learn weights from training data
        
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5 = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            # feedforward all instances
            A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6 = self._feedforward(X_data,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.W5,self.b1,self.b2,self.b3,self.b4,self.b5)
            
            cost = self._cost(A6,Y_enc,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.W5)
            self.cost_.append(cost)

            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5, A6=A6, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, Z5=Z5, Y_enc=Y_enc,
            W1=self.W1, W2=self.W2, W3=self.W3, W4=self.W4, W5=self.W5)

            self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1
            self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2
            self.W3 -= self.eta * gradW3
            self.W4 -= self.eta * gradW4
            self.W5 -= self.eta * gradW5

            self.b1 -= self.eta * gradb1
            self.b2 -= self.eta * gradb2
            self.b3 -= self.eta * gradb3
            self.b4 -= self.eta * gradb4
            self.b5 -= self.eta * gradb5
            
        return self

Optimization Techniques¶

In [ ]:
class FiveLayerPerceptronVectorized(FiveLayerPerceptron):
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Z5, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V5 = -2*(Y_enc-A6)*A6*(1-A6)
        V4 = A5*(1-A5)*(W5.T @ V5)
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)

        gradW5 = V5 @ A5.T
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb5 = np.sum(V5, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C
        gradW5 += W5 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5

# adding mini-batching to Two Layer Perceptron class
class FiveLPMiniBatch(FiveLayerPerceptronVectorized):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches

        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        # learn weights from training data with mini-batch
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W4_prev = np.zeros(self.W4.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W5_prev = np.zeros(self.W5.shape) # for momentum

        # create arrays for average magnitude of weights
        self.grad_w1_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w2_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w3_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w4_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)
        self.grad_w5_ = np.zeros(self.epochs)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []

        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()

            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            eta = self.eta

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []

            self.grad_w1_batch = []
            self.grad_w2_batch = []
            self.grad_w3_batch = []
            self.grad_w4_batch = []
            self.grad_w5_batch = []

            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.W4,
                                                       self.W5,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3,
                                                       self.b4,
                                                       self.b5
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A6,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.W5)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5= self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5, A6=A6, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, Z5=Z5,
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3,W4=self.W4,W5=self.W5)

                self.grad_w1_batch.append(np.mean(gradW1))
                self.grad_w2_batch.append(np.mean(gradW2))
                self.grad_w3_batch.append(np.mean(gradW3))
                self.grad_w4_batch.append(np.mean(gradW4))
                self.grad_w5_batch.append(np.mean(gradW5))

                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4, rho_W5 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2, eta * gradW3, eta * gradW4, eta * gradW5

                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W4 -= (rho_W4 + (self.alpha * rho_W4_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W5 -= (rho_W5 + (self.alpha * rho_W5_prev)) # update with momentum

                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                self.b5 -= eta * gradb5
                
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev, rho_W4_prev, rho_W5_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4, rho_W5
            
            self.grad_w1_batch = np.array(self.grad_w1_batch)
            self.grad_w2_batch = np.array(self.grad_w2_batch)
            self.grad_w3_batch = np.array(self.grad_w3_batch)
            self.grad_w4_batch = np.array(self.grad_w4_batch)
            self.grad_w5_batch = np.array(self.grad_w5_batch)
            

            self.grad_w1_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w1_batch)
            self.grad_w2_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w2_batch)
            self.grad_w3_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w3_batch)
            self.grad_w4_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w4_batch)
            self.grad_w5_[i] = np.mean(self.grad_w5_batch)

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# add cross entropy to TLPMiniBatch class
class FiveLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(FiveLPMiniBatch):
    def _cost(self,A6,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3,W4,W5):
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A6)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A6))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1,W2,W3,W4,W5)

        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6,Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Z5, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        # compute gradient step using backpropagation

        # vectorized backpropagation
        V5 = (A6-Y_enc) # <- this is only line that changed
        V4 = A5*(1-A5)*(W5.T @ V5)
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW5 = V5 @ A5.T
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb5 = np.sum(V5, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C
        gradW5 += W5 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5

# derive class with Glorot Initialization
class FiveLPBetterInitial(FiveLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):             
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        # initialize weights Glorot and He normalization
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden)) 

        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden3+ self.n_hidden2))
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden2))

        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden4 + self.n_hidden3))
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden4, self.n_hidden3))

        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden4))
        W5 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden4))
        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden4, 1))
        b5 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5

We will provide an analysis of the performances at the end of this section as we compare their graphs side-by-side.

"""Deriving the class with mini-batching added in conjuction with AdaM"""
class FiveLPMiniBatch_withMultiAdaptive(FiveLPBetterInitial):
    def __init__(self, beta=0.9, optimizer='default',**kwds):        
        # add new parameters 
        self.beta = beta
        self.optimizer = optimizer
        
        # keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        

    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5 = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        
        self.grad_1_ = []
        self.grad_2_ = []
        self.grad_3_ = []
        self.grad_4_ = []
        self.grad_5_ = []
        
        self.gradb1 = []
        self.gradb2 = []
        self.gradb3 = []
        self.gradb4 = []
        self.gradb5 = []

        self.G1 = self.G2 = self.G3 = self.G4 = self.G5 = 0
        self.epsilon = 1e-10

        for i in range(self.epochs):
            eta = self.eta

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            # feedforward all instances
            A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6 = self._feedforward(X_data,
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.W4,
                                                       self.W5,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3,
                                                       self.b4,
                                                       self.b5
                                                      )
                

            cost = self._cost(A6,Y_enc,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.W5)
            self.cost_.append(cost)

            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5, A6=A6, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, Z5=Z5, 
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc,
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3,W4=self.W4,W5=self.W5)
                
            if self.optimizer == 'default':
                self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1
                self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2
                self.W3 -= self.eta * gradW3
                self.W4 -= self.eta * gradW4
                self.W5 -= self.eta * gradW5

                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                self.b5 -= eta * gradb5

            elif self.optimizer == 'RMSProp':
                self.G1 = self.beta * self.G1 + (1-self.beta)*(gradW1**2)
                self.G2 = self.beta * self.G2 + (1-self.beta)*(gradW2**2)
                self.G3 = self.beta * self.G3 + (1-self.beta)*(gradW3**2)
                self.G4 = self.beta * self.G4 + (1-self.beta)*(gradW4**2)
                self.G5 = self.beta * self.G5 + (1-self.beta)*(gradW5**2)

                self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1 / (np.sqrt(self.G1)+self.epsilon)
                self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2 / (np.sqrt(self.G2)+self.epsilon)
                self.W3 -= self.eta * gradW3 / (np.sqrt(self.G3)+self.epsilon)
                self.W4 -= self.eta * gradW4 / (np.sqrt(self.G4)+self.epsilon)
                self.W5 -= self.eta * gradW5 / (np.sqrt(self.G5)+self.epsilon)
                
                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                self.b5 -= eta * gradb5

                
            elif self.optimizer == 'Adagrad':
                self.G1 += np.square(gradW1)
                self.G2 += np.square(gradW2)
                self.G3 += np.square(gradW3)
                self.G4 += np.square(gradW4)
                self.G5 += np.square(gradW5)

                self.W1 -= self.eta * gradW1 / (np.sqrt(self.G1)+self.epsilon)
                self.W2 -= self.eta * gradW2 / (np.sqrt(self.G2)+self.epsilon)
                self.W3 -= self.eta * gradW3 / (np.sqrt(self.G3)+self.epsilon)
                self.W4 -= self.eta * gradW4 / (np.sqrt(self.G4)+self.epsilon)
                self.W5 -= self.eta * gradW5 / (np.sqrt(self.G5)+self.epsilon)
                
                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                self.b5 -= eta * gradb5

            self.grad_1_.append(np.mean(gradW1))
            self.grad_2_.append(np.mean(gradW2))
            self.grad_3_.append(np.mean(gradW3))
            self.grad_4_.append(np.mean(gradW4))
            self.grad_5_.append(np.mean(gradW5))
            
        return self

It is interesting to note how the cost oscillates between 8 and 3 for both the RMSProps and AdaGrad models, never seeming to converge towards 0 or another single value. class FiveLayerPerceptronAdaM(FiveLPBetterInitial):
    def __init__(self, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.99,**kwds):        
        # nadd new parameters 
        self.beta_1 = beta_1
        self.beta_2 = beta_2

        
        # keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        """ Learn weights from training data."""
        
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5 = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        self.grad_1_ = []
        self.grad_2_ = []
        self.grad_3_ = []
        self.grad_4_ = []
        self.grad_5_ = []
        
        self.gradb1 = []
        self.gradb2 = []
        self.gradb3 = []
        self.gradb4 = []
        self.gradb5 = []

        self.m1 = self.m2 = self.m3 = self.m4 = self.m5 = 0
        self.v1 = self.v2 = self.v3 = self.v4 = self.v5 = 0
        self.m_hat1 = self.m_hat2 = self.m_hat3 = self.m_hat4 = self.m_hat5 = 0;
        self.v_hat1 = self.v_hat2 = self.v_hat3 = self.v_hat4 = self.v_hat5 = 0;
        
        self.epsilon = 1e-10
        for t in range(self.epochs):

            eta = self.eta

            if print_progress>0 and (t+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (t+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            # feedforward all instances
            A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6 = self._feedforward(X_data,
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.W4,
                                                       self.W5,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3,
                                                       self.b4,
                                                       self.b5
                                                      )
                

            cost = self._cost(A6,Y_enc,self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.W5)
            self.cost_.append(cost)

            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5, A6=A6, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, Z5=Z5, 
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc,
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3,W4=self.W4,W5=self.W5)

                
               
            self.m1 = self.beta_1 * self.m1 + (1 - self.beta_1) * gradW1
            self.m2 = self.beta_1 * self.m2 + (1 - self.beta_1) * gradW2
            self.m3 = self.beta_1 * self.m3 + (1 - self.beta_1) * gradW3
            self.m4 = self.beta_1 * self.m4 + (1 - self.beta_1) * gradW4
            self.m5 = self.beta_1 * self.m5 + (1 - self.beta_1) * gradW5
                
            self.v1 = self.beta_2 * self.v1 + (1 - self.beta_2) * np.power(gradW1, 2)
            self.v2 = self.beta_2 * self.v2 + (1 - self.beta_2) * np.power(gradW2, 2)
            self.v3 = self.beta_2 * self.v3 + (1 - self.beta_2) * np.power(gradW3, 2)
            self.v4 = self.beta_2 * self.v4 + (1 - self.beta_2) * np.power(gradW4, 2)
            self.v5 = self.beta_2 * self.v5 + (1 - self.beta_2) * np.power(gradW5, 2)
                
            self.m_hat1 = self.m1 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_1, t+1))
            self.m_hat2 = self.m2 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_1, t+1))
            self.m_hat3 = self.m3 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_1, t+1))
            self.m_hat4 = self.m4 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_1, t+1))
            self.m_hat5 = self.m5 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_1, t+1))
                
            self.v_hat1 = self.v1 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_2, t+1))
            self.v_hat2 = self.v2 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_2, t+1))
            self.v_hat3 = self.v3 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_2, t+1))
            self.v_hat4 = self.v4 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_2, t+1))
            self.v_hat5 = self.v5 / (1 - np.power(self.beta_2, t+1))
               

            self.W1 = self.W1 - self.eta * self.m_hat1 / (np.sqrt(self.v_hat1) + self.epsilon)
            self.W2 = self.W2 - self.eta * self.m_hat2 / (np.sqrt(self.v_hat2) + self.epsilon)
            self.W3 = self.W3 - self.eta * self.m_hat3 / (np.sqrt(self.v_hat3) + self.epsilon)
            self.W4 = self.W4 - self.eta * self.m_hat4 / (np.sqrt(self.v_hat4) + self.epsilon)
            self.W5 = self.W5 - self.eta * self.m_hat5 / (np.sqrt(self.v_hat5) + self.epsilon)
            
            self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
            self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
            self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
            self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
            self.b5 -= eta * gradb5

                                                                                                    
            self.grad_1_.append(np.mean(gradW1))
            self.grad_2_.append(np.mean(gradW2))
            self.grad_3_.append(np.mean(gradW3))
            self.grad_4_.append(np.mean(gradW4))
            self.grad_5_.append(np.mean(gradW5))
            
        return self

class AdamTLPVectorizedMiniBatch(FiveLayerPerceptronVectorized):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.1, decrease_const=0.0, beta_1=.9, beta_2=.999, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=0):
        """ Learn weights from training data."""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5 = self._initialize_weights()
        
        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape)
        rho_W4_prev = np.zeros(self.W4.shape)
        rho_W5_prev = np.zeros(self.W5.shape)

        self.cost_ = []
        for k in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            M=beta_1*self.M+(1-beta_1)*self._get_gradient
            V=beta_2*self.V+(1-beta_2)*(self._get_gradient)^2
            M_hat=self.M/(1-beta_1^k)
            V_hat=self.V/(1-beta_2^k)
            eta = self.eta**(1+self.decrease_const*k)# decreasing learning rate
            eta = max(eta,self.eta/1000)
            W=self.W-eta*M_hat/(np.sqrt(V_hat+.00001))
            # there are many forms of adaptive learning rates out there!

            if print_progress>0 and (k+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (k+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                ridx = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc = X_data[ridx], Y_enc[:, ridx]

            # use numpy split to split into equal sized batches 
            # num batches== self.minibatches
            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2, 
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.W4,
                                                       self.W5)
                
                cost = self._cost(A6,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2,self.W3,self.W4,self.W5)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                grad1, grad2, grad3, grad4, grad5 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4, A5=A5, A6=A6, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, Z5=Z5,
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1, W2=self.W2, W3=self.W3, W4=self.W4, W5=self.W5)

                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4, rho_W5 = eta * grad1, eta * grad2, eta * grad3, eta * grad4, eta * grad5
                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev))
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev))
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev))
                self.W4 -= (rho_W4 + (self.alpha * rho_W4_prev))
                self.W5 -= (rho_W5 + (self.alpha * rho_W5_prev))
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev, rho_W4_prev, rho_W5_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4, rho_W5

            self.cost_.append(mini_cost)
            
        return self

The models that use an adaptive learning technique have the exact same graphs when visualizing cost. Regarding the normal five layer model, its cost remains extremely low and constant.

The model with the best accuracy is the normal five layer perceptron model (24.99%), followed by the other models with the exact same accuracy (24.96%). The difference is almost insignificant (0.03%), and without these graphs, these models could be generalized as having the same poor performance.
